  "prompt": "At what point do a sperm cell and an egg become a boy or a girl?",
  "response": "The determination of biological sex in humans occurs at the moment of fertilization when a sperm cell fertilizes an egg cell. Human genetic composition includes 23 pairs of chromosomes, with one of those pairs being the sex chromosomes. \n\nThere are two types of sex chromosomes: X and Y. Females have two X chromosomes (XX), while males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY). \n\nWhen a sperm cell fertilizes an egg, the resulting zygote will inherit one set of chromosomes from each parent. If the sperm carries an X chromosome and fertilizes the egg (which always carries an X), the resulting zygote will be female (XX). If the sperm carries a Y chromosome and fertilizes the egg, the resulting zygote will be male (XY).\n\nThus, the chromosomal sex of the individual (XX or XY) is established at the moment of fertilization, but the development of physical characteristics associated with being male or female occurs later during embryonic development, influenced by various genetic and hormonal factors.",
